The United States Paradigm: The OCC and Federal Reserve Mandates
Within the United States regulatory framework, the expectation for a documented, highly structured risk identification methodology is explicitly codified in foundational supervisory guidance. Furthermore, the failure to implement such methodologies has been the primary focal point of the most severe and high-profile regulatory enforcement actions executed over the past decade.
Federal Reserve SR 15-18: The Mandate for a Formal, Dynamic Process
The Federal Reserve’s Supervisory Letter SR 15-18, which outlines the comprehensive capital planning expectations for large financial institutions, places risk identification at the absolute center of a bank's capital adequacy [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf]. The regulatory logic underpinning this guidance is straightforward: a bank's capital planning and stress testing cannot possibly be sound if the underlying risks requiring capitalization have not been comprehensively and systematically identified in the first place.
SR 15-18 explicitly demands that the risk identification process be dynamic, inclusive, and comprehensive, driving the entirety of the firm's capital adequacy analysis [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf]. The Federal Reserve draws a sharp distinction between different tiers of supervised institutions, imposing the most stringent methodological requirements on Category I standards, which apply to United States Global Systemically Important Banks. For these institutions, senior management is required to formally review the risk identification and capital planning process on a quarterly basis, ensuring that the identification of risk is a continuous operational cadence rather than a static annual exercise [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf].
The specific methodology requirements articulated within the attachment to SR 15-18 are exacting. A supervised firm must establish a formal risk identification process that explicitly details how the firm captures difficult-to-quantify risks, segmenting them at highly granular levels to ensure nothing is obscured by high-level aggregation [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf]. The Federal Reserve expects the methodology to mandate the continuous involvement of multiple stakeholders from across the entire enterprise. This requirement ensures that risk identification is never a siloed exercise conducted solely by the second line of defense in a vacuum, but rather a deeply collaborative process that extracts nuanced insights directly from the front-line business units that originate the risk exposures [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf]. Furthermore, the methodology must rigorously document how these specifically identified risks are mapped directly into the firm's stress scenario design. The scenario narrative must explicitly describe how the stress test addresses the firm's particular material risks and vulnerabilities, creating a closed-loop system where identification directly informs and validates capital measurement [https://www.federalreserve.gov/supervisionreg/srletters/sr1518_pw.pdf].
The Federal Reserve's findings in its continuous supervisory activities echo these strict requirements. In its November 2018 Supervision and Regulation Report, which detailed the condition of Large Institution Supervision Coordinating Committee firms and Large and Foreign Banking Organizations, the Federal Reserve explicitly noted that nearly seventy percent of all supervisory findings were related to governance and controls [https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/201811-supervision-and-regulation-report.pdf]. Specifically, the report highlighted pervasive deficiencies and weaknesses in liquidity risk identification processes, demonstrating that even the largest institutions struggled to formalize how they identified severe funding vulnerabilities before they materialized [https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/files/201811-supervision-and-regulation-report.pdf].
OCC Heightened Standards: Codifying the Three Lines of Defense
The Office of the Comptroller of the Currency addresses the necessity of risk identification methodologies through its "Heightened Standards" for large insured national banks, which are codified in 12 CFR Part 30, Appendix D. The Heightened Standards legally enforce the "Three Lines of Defense" operational model and place highly specific, stringent methodological requirements on each individual line regarding how they identify and process risk.
According to the text of Appendix D, the Front Line Units, acting as the first line of defense, hold the primary, non-delegable responsibility for assessing material risks on a continuous, ongoing basis. These business units are explicitly required to establish written policies that ensure risks are effectively identified, measured, monitored, and controlled. This constitutes a clear, direct regulatory demand for a documented risk identification methodology precisely at the point of risk origination, preventing business lines from abdicating this responsibility to the oversight functions.
Simultaneously, Independent Risk Management, acting as the second line of defense, is mandated to design, review, and update the overarching risk governance framework at least annually. This review must specifically address changes in the bank's risk profile caused by emerging risks, internal operational shifts, or external macroeconomic factors. Satisfying this requirement necessitates a formalized, methodological approach to horizon scanning. The second line cannot merely react to risks identified by the front line; it must deploy its own methodology to independently verify that the risk inventory is complete. Furthermore, the OCC expects banks to maintain robust risk data aggregation capabilities specifically designed to capture and aggregate risk data so that material risks and dangerous portfolio concentrations can be reported to the board of directors in a timely manner. Without a clearly defined and documented methodology establishing what constitutes a "material risk" or a "concentration," the bank's data aggregation infrastructure lacks the foundational parameters required to function effectively.
Model Risk Management (Fed SR 11-7): The Precursor to Methodological Rigor
The regulatory demand for a documented identification process was largely pioneered and refined in the domain of model risk management, guided by the Federal Reserve's SR 11-7 and the corresponding OCC Bulletin 2011-12 [https://www.occ.treas.gov/publications-and-resources/publications/comptrollers-handbook/files/model-risk-management/pub-ch-model-risk.pdf]. Prior to this guidance, banks viewed models merely as calculators, failing to recognize them as distinct sources of enterprise risk. SR 11-7 revolutionized this view by demanding that banks treat the use of models as an inherent vulnerability requiring a strict management methodology.
The model risk guidelines require banks to establish a comprehensive methodology for identifying when a quantitative tool actually qualifies as a model, effectively forcing the institution to document its identification perimeter [https://www.occ.treas.gov/publications-and-resources/publications/comptrollers-handbook/files/model-risk-management/pub-ch-model-risk.pdf]. Once a model is identified, the methodology requires a documented process for identifying its inherent limitations, the assumptions upon which it relies, and the specific market conditions under which the model will break down or produce inaccurate outputs. This requirement to systematically identify limitations and apply compensating controls serves as the exact conceptual blueprint that regulators now expect banks to apply to the identification of enterprise-wide non-financial risks.
The Enforcement Reality: Wells Fargo and Citigroup
The profound operational gap between possessing a static risk register and deploying a dynamic risk identification methodology is most starkly illustrated in the landmark enforcement actions levied against major US institutions.
In February 2018, the Federal Reserve issued an unprecedented and severe consent cease-and-desist order against Wells Fargo & Company, restricting the massive financial institution's total asset growth until it demonstrably remediated deep-seated weaknesses in its corporate governance, risk management, and internal controls [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20180202a1.pdf]. The core of the Federal Reserve's findings was not simply that Wells Fargo had taken on excessive compliance and reputational risk through its widespread retail sales practices, but that its enterprise-wide framework catastrophically failed to properly identify, aggregate, and escalate those risks to the board of directors [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20180202a1.pdf].
The Federal Reserve mandated the implementation of a fundamentally improved firmwide program explicitly designed to identify and manage risks across the consolidated organization. The regulatory findings explicitly noted that Wells Fargo lacked an effective framework that identifies, aggregates, evaluates, and appropriately reports material risk issues [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20180202a1.pdf]. The failure was fundamentally methodological: there was no systematic, repeatable process linking the massive consumer compliance failures occurring daily in the retail branches to the sanitized enterprise risk registers being reviewed by the Board of Directors. Consequently, the Federal Reserve explicitly required the bank to implement a well-controlled key risk indicator program that was directly linked to the firm's risk identification and risk tolerance processes [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20180202a1.pdf]. The OCC's parallel investigations supported this, finding that risk management processes were so highly decentralized, siloed, and undocumented that senior executives completely failed to identify the root causes of the misconduct, treating widespread sales practice violations as isolated human resources issues rather than acknowledging them as systemic, enterprise-wide risks [https://oig.treasury.gov/system/files/2021-02/OIG-20-046.pdf].
Similarly, in October 2020, the Federal Reserve and the OCC issued sweeping, coordinated enforcement actions against Citigroup, citing longstanding deficiencies in the bank's risk management and internal controls. The Federal Reserve’s cease-and-desist order required Citigroup to conduct a comprehensive "Gap Analysis" of its enterprise-wide risk management framework, specifically demanding that the firm identify exactly where its risk management policies, procedures, and practices were insufficient to meet regulatory expectations under Regulation YY [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20201007a1.pdf]. The OCC’s parallel order focused intensely on data quality management and its direct impact on risk identification. The regulators found that without a robust, modern data architecture—a fundamental methodological necessity for accurate risk identification—the bank simply could not accurately identify its aggregate risk exposures [https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/enf20201007a1.pdf]. Citigroup was subsequently forced to undertake a massive, multi-year transformation program to completely redesign its enterprise risk assessment framework to capture and aggregate the results of all relevant risk identification inputs reliably across the globe [https://www.occ.gov/static/enforcement-actions/ea2020-037.pdf].
The United Kingdom Paradigm: The PRA's Evolving Expectations
The United Kingdom’s Prudential Regulation Authority has been arguably the most vocal and philosophically consistent regulator globally regarding the need for dynamic, documented risk management processes. Through formal supervisory statements, thematic reviews, and highly direct communications with bank executives, the PRA continually emphasizes that identifying risk is a continuous operational process, not a static reporting deliverable.
SS31/15: The ICAAP Risk Identification Mandate
The PRA's Supervisory Statement SS31/15 forms the cornerstone of its expectations for the Internal Capital Adequacy Assessment Process [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2015/ss3115.pdf]. The ICAAP is the ultimate test of a bank's risk identification methodology, as it legally requires the firm to assess all material risks inherent in its business model to determine appropriate, forward-looking capital levels.
SS31/15 sets stringent expectations that firms must proactively identify specific vulnerabilities embedded within their portfolios. For instance, the PRA expects firms to implement a methodology that systematically identifies illiquid, one-way, or highly concentrated positions, and to then stress these identified positions over appropriate holding periods and confidence levels [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2015/ss3115.pdf]. This expectation requires a methodology capable of defining exactly what constitutes a "concentrated position" and establishing the data lineage necessary to detect it dynamically as market conditions shift.
Furthermore, the PRA explicitly states that during the Supervisory Review and Evaluation Process, it will closely assess the appropriateness of the internal processes, governance arrangements, and systems utilized for supporting and producing the ICAAP [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2015/ss3115.pdf]. If a supervised firm simply produces a list of risks and a final capital number without exhaustively demonstrating the governance arrangements, data systems, and internal challenge processes used to identify those risks, the ICAAP will be deemed structurally deficient. This deficiency almost invariably results in the imposition of a severe Pillar 2 capital add-on, penalizing the bank for its methodological opacity.
Model Risk Management (SS1/23): Formalizing the Identification Framework
The PRA’s recent and intense focus on Model Risk Management, codified in the sweeping Supervisory Statement SS1/23, provides a perfect microcosm of the broader regulatory frustration with enterprise risk identification. Just as banks have historically struggled to define exactly how they identify enterprise risks, they have similarly struggled to systematically identify model risks across complex, decentralized global operations.
SS1/23 demands a highly formalized, heavily documented methodology for managing model risk. It explicitly requires banks to establish a clear, documented definition of what constitutes a "model" and what constitutes "model risk" to ensure consistent identification across all business lines [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2023/ss123.pdf]. Firms must document and maintain a "model tiering" approach to systematically identify and classify all models based on their inherent materiality and computational complexity [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2023/ss123.pdf].
Crucially, the PRA requires banks to implement rigorous standards for conducting root cause analyses to systematically identify model limitations and the systemic causes of any performance deterioration [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2023/ss123.pdf]. SS1/23 explicitly mandates deep process documentation: firms must implement robust policies covering development standards, data management and quality, independent validation procedures, and change governance [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2023/ss123.pdf]. By forcing banks to document the precise methodology of how a model is identified, classified, and continually validated, the PRA is applying the exact same regulatory logic and demand for rigor that it expects for enterprise-wide risk identification.
Dear CEO Letters and Speeches: The Constant Drumbeat of Governance
The PRA regularly communicates its thematic findings and supervisory frustrations to the industry via public "Dear CEO" letters, and the lack of robust risk identification processes has been a recurring, prominent theme in these communications from 2018 through 2025.
In its letters setting out the supervisory priorities for both international banks operating in the UK and domestic UK deposit-takers, the PRA repeatedly highlights pervasive, ongoing weaknesses in basic risk management, governance, and internal controls. The PRA explicitly states its expectation that boards of directors deeply consider where the institution's underlying "risk culture" may be the root cause of material weaknesses in the firm's control environment [https://www.regulationtomorrow.com/eu/pra-dear-ceo-letter-on-2025-priorities-for-supervising-uk-deposit-takers/]. A poor risk culture is almost always characterized by a "tick-box" compliance approach to updating risk registers, rather than a genuine, intellectually curious, and well-documented methodology for proactively uncovering structural threats.
As in the European Union, the emergence of climate change as a financial threat has been a major focal point for the PRA, serving to expose the inadequacy of existing risk identification methodologies. In a series of letters and speeches spanning several years, PRA CEO Sam Woods highlighted that while banks were beginning to make progress, massive capability gaps remained in core areas, specifically pointing to risk identification and measurement as deficient [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/letter/2020/managing-the-financial-risks-from-climate-change.pdf].
The PRA found that many banks entirely lacked a climate-specific risk appetite and failed to establish any climate-related risk metrics, making it procedurally impossible to systematically identify when a climate risk breached a management tolerance threshold [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/prudential-regulation/publication/2025/april/enhancing-banks-and-insurers-approaches-to-managing-climate-related-risks-consultation-paper]. To correct this, the PRA’s Supervisory Statement SS5/25 directly instructs firms to apply a formalized "two-step process" that begins explicitly with "Risk identification, assessment and sign-off," expecting firms to use advanced scenario analysis not just as a stress testing output, but as a primary methodological tool to actively identify hidden vulnerabilities in their current business models [https://www.bankofengland.co.uk/-/media/boe/files/prudential-regulation/supervisory-statement/2025/ss425-december-2025.pdf].
The European Union Paradigm: The EBA and ECB Supervisory Review
Across the English Channel, European regulators share the exact same systemic concerns regarding the opacity of risk identification methodologies. Both the European Banking Authority and the European Central Bank have increasingly focused their immense supervisory firepower on the structural mechanisms by which banks uncover, debate, and classify risk.
EBA Guidelines on Internal Governance (EBA/GL/2021/05)
The EBA Guidelines on Internal Governance represent the foundational, harmonizing text for how all European banks must structure their internal control and risk processes. The guidelines explicitly and legally place the ultimate responsibility for risk identification squarely on the management body, requiring them to establish, maintain, and implement a sound risk strategy and a comprehensive risk management framework.
Crucially, the EBA demands the establishment of a formal, highly independent Risk Management Function tasked explicitly with the duties of identifying, measuring, assessing, managing, mitigating, monitoring, and reporting risks. The guidelines emphasize that a primary aim of the internal governance framework is to ensure a holistic view of all risks through the implementation of a "uniform methodology and terminology". This constitutes a direct, unambiguous regulatory mandate for a documented methodology. A uniform terminology—a formalized risk taxonomy—is the absolute prerequisite for any repeatable identification process. Without it, risks cannot be aggregated or compared across different European jurisdictions or business lines.
Furthermore, the EBA guidelines require that the Risk Management Function play a highly active, documented role in identifying the specific risks related to material changes in the business, such as the introduction of new products or the creation of complex, opaque intra-group structures. This requirement prevents banks from relying on ad-hoc, informal assessments when expanding their business models, forcing them instead to run any new ventures through a pre-defined, rigorous risk identification gauntlet. EBA peer reviews have historically noted that without these harmonized guidelines, supervisory practices and governance assessments diverge wildly across national competent authorities, allowing banks to exploit methodological loopholes.
ECB SREP Findings: The Methodology Gap
The ECB’s Supervisory Review and Evaluation Process is the critical annual health check for all significant institutions operating within the Eurozone. The aggregate findings published from the 2022 through 2025 SREP cycles consistently and prominently highlight deep-seated deficiencies in bank risk identification frameworks.
Within the ECB's own internal methodology for conducting the SREP, risk identification is heavily scrutinized. For example, regarding the assessment of market risk, Joint Supervisory Teams are instructed to assess whether institutions have an appropriate and well-documented framework, explicitly including policies and procedures, for identifying and measuring market risk [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/activities/srep/2024/html/ssm.srep202412_marketrisksrepmethodology.en.html]. Similarly, for operational and IT risk, the explicit supervisory expectation is that banks have a risk identification process that is comprehensive and operationally effective in understanding and capturing all material operational risks inherent in their specific products, activities, processes, and systems [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/activities/srep/2024/html/ssm.srep202412_operationalandictriskmethodology.en.html].
Despite these clear, published expectations, the ECB’s aggregate results paint a troubling picture of ongoing methodological struggles across the continent. SREP reports from 2023 and 2024 identified highly common findings related to weak management awareness of risk, a profound lack of clear and well-designed processes, and a widespread shortage of internal policies governing risk identification. The ECB specifically noted that many banks possess high-level risk appetite statements that are simply not granular enough to capture all material risks, which is a direct, unavoidable consequence of a flawed and superficial underlying identification methodology.
In the 2025 SREP results, while the ECB noted stable overall scoring across the sector, it highlighted that qualitative supervisory measures were frequently issued to address persistent deficiencies in the enhancement of the stress testing framework within the ICAAP. The ECB explicitly tied these stress testing weaknesses to the unreliability of the underlying risk identification inputs [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/activities/srep/2025/html/ssm.srep202511_aggregatedresults2025.en.html].
The Climate Risk Catalyst
Perhaps nothing in modern financial history has exposed the banking sector's lack of repeatable risk identification methodologies quite like the rapid emergence of climate-related and environmental risks. Because climate risks are entirely novel, inherently non-linear, and rely heavily on forward-looking data models rather than historical loss datasets, static risk registers were entirely unequipped to identify or handle them.
The ECB’s comprehensive "Guide on climate-related and environmental risks" explicitly targets this massive methodology gap. Expectation 4 of the Guide requires institutions to explicitly include climate-related and environmental risks in their formal risk appetite framework [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.202011finalguideonclimate-relatedandenvironmentalrisks~58213f6564.en.pdf]. More importantly, Expectation 7 mandates that institutions identify and quantify these risks within their overall process for ensuring capital adequacy, expressly forbidding banks from excluding these risks simply because they are difficult to quantify or because historical loss data is unavailable [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.202011finalguideonclimate-relatedandenvironmentalrisks~58213f6564.en.pdf].
To overcome the lack of historical data, the ECB requires banks to utilize plausible assumptions, proxies, and advanced scenario analysis as a core part of their identification methodology [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.202011finalguideonclimate-relatedandenvironmentalrisks~58213f6564.en.pdf]. The Guide details highly specific risk drivers—such as rapid policy changes, technological shifts, changing market sentiment, and acute or chronic physical risks—that must be systematically identified and mapped directly to traditional risk categories like credit, market, and operational risk [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.202011finalguideonclimate-relatedandenvironmentalrisks~58213f6564.en.pdf].
However, thematic reviews conducted subsequently by the ECB revealed massive, systemic methodological shortcomings in this area. The 2024 SREP review found that while many banks had established foundational frameworks, significant weaknesses persisted in the full integration of climate risks into core risk management frameworks and IT reporting systems [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/activities/srep/2025/html/ssm.srep202511_aggregatedresults2025.en.html]. The ECB observed that while banks were perfectly willing to add "climate change" as a high-level line item on a corporate risk register, they completely lacked the granular methodology required to identify exactly how a specific transition risk would manifest as an increased Probability of Default within a specific, concentrated corporate loan portfolio [https://www.bankingsupervision.europa.eu/ecb/pub/pdf/ssm.202011finalguideonclimate-relatedandenvironmentalrisks~58213f6564.en.pdf].
Global Standards: The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision
Underpinning the specific jurisdictional rules of the Federal Reserve, the ECB, and the PRA are the foundational global standards set by the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision. The BCBS frameworks explicitly address the absolute necessity of documented, robust risk identification methodologies to maintain global financial stability.
Principles for the Sound Management of Operational Risk
The BCBS Principles for the Sound Management of Operational Risk, which were heavily revised and updated in 2021 to reflect modern realities, dedicate Principle 6 entirely to the critical mechanics of risk identification and assessment [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf]. The Committee emphatically states that senior management must ensure the comprehensive identification and assessment of the operational risk inherent in all material products, activities, processes, and systems to ensure that the inherent risks and incentives are well understood across the enterprise [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf].
The BCBS does not merely mandate identification; it outlines highly specific methodological tools that banks are expected to utilize as part of a formal, repeatable process. These include the implementation of event management protocols, which are documented procedures for identifying, analyzing, and reporting operational risk events, specifically including root-cause analysis to identify new, previously unseen risks stemming from near-misses [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf]. Furthermore, banks must deploy Risk and Control Self-Assessments. RCSAs provide a structured methodology utilizing rigorous business process mapping to identify key operational steps and inherent vulnerabilities long before any mitigating controls are evaluated or applied [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf].
The guidelines also demand the use of scenario analysis, which involves conducting structured workshops with subject matter experts to systematically identify low-probability but high-severity events that historical data would miss [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf]. Finally, the methodology must include the development of quantitative metrics and benchmarking, utilizing Key Risk Indicators that act as early warning systems to identify shifting risk profiles in real-time [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d515.pdf]. In the eyes of the BCBS, the risk register is never the end goal; it is merely a reporting tool utilized to facilitate board oversight within a much broader, highly active ecosystem of risk identification methodologies. This is reinforced by the BCBS Corporate Governance Principles for Banks (2015), which place the ultimate onus on the board of directors to approve the risk identification framework and ensure it permeates the institution's underlying risk culture.
BCBS 239: Risk Data Aggregation and Risk Reporting
Perhaps the most structurally profound global regulation impacting how banks approach risk identification methodology is BCBS 239, the Principles for effective risk data aggregation and risk reporting. Originally issued in 2013 as a direct response to the data failures of the 2008 crisis, regulators continue to find severe compliance deficiencies a full decade later, frequently penalizing banks for their inability to aggregate exposures during stress [https://www.bis.org/bcbs/publ/d559.pdf].
While BCBS 239 is often fundamentally viewed as an IT data architecture and systems regulation, it carries massive, unavoidable implications for risk identification methodology. Principle 1 of the framework requires banks to comprehensively define their risk data needs and ensure their IT systems can capture all material risks [https://www.ovaledge.com/blog/bcbs-239-principles]. However, a bank simply cannot build a data architecture to aggregate risk data if it does not possess a strict, documented methodology to identify what constitutes a risk in the first place.
If a bank relies on an informal, undocumented process where department heads manually type risks into a spreadsheet register based purely on gut feeling or historical habit, it is technologically impossible to establish the automated data lineage and reporting pipelines required by BCBS 239 [https://www.collibra.com/blog/the-fading-flame-why-data-governance-under-bcbs-239-needs-your-attention-now]. Regulators routinely find that banks fail their BCBS 239 audits precisely because their risk identification processes are ad-hoc and unstandardized. This methodological failure makes it impossible to systematically tag, aggregate, and report those risks across global legal entities rapidly during times of severe market stress. Robust risk identification methodology is, therefore, the absolute necessary prerequisite for risk data aggregation.
The Root Causes of the Methodology Deficit
If prudential regulators across the globe have been uniformly demanding documented risk identification methodologies for over a decade, why do sophisticated financial institutions continually fail to produce them? An analysis of supervisory findings and enforcement actions points to several deeply ingrained structural, cultural, and psychological root causes within the banking sector.
Common Methodological Failure Mode
	Symptom Observable in the Enterprise
	Direct Regulatory Finding or Consequence
	Siloed Risk Taxonomies
	The capital markets trading desk and the retail banking branch define and measure "cyber risk" using entirely different metrics and definitions.
